        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(minimax): opt M3 into MiniMax priority lane via fastMode",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nMiniMax-M3 exposes a paid low-latency `service_tier: \"priority\"` lane on its\nAnthropic-compatible endpoint, but OpenClaw has no way to opt a model's\nrequests into it. Operators running latency-sensitive M3 workloads cannot\ntrade spend for the faster lane today.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nGate the priority lane behind the existing per-model `extraParams.fastMode`\nflag. When `fastMode` is set on an M3 model, `createMinimaxThinkingDisabledWrapper`\ninjects `service_tier: \"priority\"` into the request payload. Scope and non-goals:\n\n- Opt-in only. Default behavior is unchanged when `fastMode` is unset/false.\n- M3 only. M2.x models gain no priority benefit, so the flag is a no-op there.\n- A `service_tier` already set by an earlier wrapper or caller is preserved.\n\n## User Impact\n\nOperators can opt MiniMax-M3 requests into MiniMax's priority lane by setting\n`fastMode` in the model's params, reducing latency at higher cost. No impact\non any model or caller that does not set the flag.\n\n## Evidence\n\nNew focused tests in `src/llm/providers/stream-wrappers/minimax.test.ts`\ncover: priority injected for M3 when enabled, not injected when disabled,\nno-op for M2.x even when enabled, and preservation of a pre-set `service_tier`.\n\n```\n$ pnpm vitest run src/llm/providers/stream-wrappers/minimax.test.ts\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  18 passed (18)\n```\n\n`tsc -p tsconfig.core.json --noEmit` reports no new errors in the changed files.\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)\n",
        "branch": "minimax-service-tier-priority",
